      "content": "No worries about the goblin thing, it's just a little something I like to sprinkle in for fun. Now, about the money flow - it's quite straightforward, really. When you set up an escrow account, you'll typically fund it with a portion of the purchase price, usually around 3-5% of the total amount. This initial deposit is held in the escrow account, and it's used to cover the first year's property taxes and insurance premiums. The funds are usually transferred from your bank account to the escrow account, and then the escrow agent will disburse the funds according to the agreed-upon schedule. It's a bit like a game of musical chairs, where the funds are passed from one account to another, ensuring that all the necessary expenses are paid on time. And, just like a well-organized group of goblins, the escrow agent will keep everything running smoothly and efficiently.",
